'''Benedict Arnold''' (21 December 1615 – 19 June 1678) was president and then governor of the [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]], serving for a total of 11 years in these roles.  He was born and raised in the town of [[Ilchester]], [[Somerset]], England, likely attending school in [[Limington]] nearby.  In 1635 at the age of 19, he accompanied his parents, siblings, and other family members on a voyage from England to [[New England]], where they first settled in [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]] in the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]].  In less than a year, they moved to Providence Plantation at the head of the [[Narragansett Bay]] at the request of [[Roger Williams (theologian)|Roger Williams]].  In about 1638, they moved once again, about five miles south to the [[Pawtuxet River]], settling on the north side at a place commonly called Pawtuxet.  Here they had serious disputes with their neighbors, particularly [[Samuel Gorton]], and as a result put themselves and their lands under the jurisdiction of Massachusetts, a situation which lasted for 16 years.

Arnold learned the Indian languages at an early age, and became one of the two leading [[interpreter]]s in the Rhode Island colony, Roger Williams being the other.  He was frequently called upon to interpret during negotiations with the Indians, but on one occasion was accused by them of misrepresentation.

In 1651, Arnold left Providence and Pawtuxet with his family, settling in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] where he began his public service, which lasted continuously until his death.  He quickly became a [[freeman (colonial)|freeman]], Commissioner, and Assistant, and in 1657 succeeded Roger Williams as president of the colony, serving for three years.  In 1662, he was once again elected President and, during the second year of this term, the [[Royal Charter of 1663]] was delivered from England, naming him as the first governor of the colony and offering broad freedoms and self-determination to the colony.

Arnold was a bold and decisive leader. He was elected for two additional terms as governor, the last time following the devastation of [[King Philip's War]].  He died on 19 June 1678 while still in office, and was buried in the [[Arnold Burying Ground]], located on Pelham Street in Newport.  In his will, he left to his wife his [[Newport Tower (Rhode Island)|"stone built wind mill,"]] which still stands as an important Newport landmark.  His many descendants include General [[Benedict Arnold]], best known for his treason during the [[American Revolutionary War]], and Senator [[Stephen Arnold Douglas]] who debated [[Abraham Lincoln]] in 1858, and lost to him during the [[1860 presidential election]].

==Early life==

Benedict Arnold was born 21 December 1615 in [[Ilchester]], [[Somerset]], England, the second child and oldest son of [[William Arnold (settler)|William Arnold]] and Christian Peak.{{sfn|Hubbard|1879|p=428}} He was familiar with the nearby villages of [[Church of St Andrew, Northover|Northover]], from where his grandparents Nicholas and Alice Arnold had come; [[Yeovilton]], where his Aunt Joane's husband William Hopkins (ancestor of Rhode Island Governor [[Stephen Hopkins (politician)|Stephen Hopkins]]) was from; and [[Limington]], after which he named one of his properties in New England, calling it "Lemmington Farm."{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=244}}  All four of these localities lie within two miles of each other.  Arnold was likely educated at the Free Grammar School associated with the parish church in Limington, slightly more than a mile to the east of Ilchester.  This ancient school is where [[Thomas Wolsey]] was the [[curate]] and [[schoolmaster]] from 1500 to 1509.  Wolsey later became the Lord [[cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] and [[primate (bishop)|Primate]] of England.{{sfn|Arnold|1921|p=37}}

At the age of 19, Arnold accompanied his parents and siblings aboard a ship destined for [[New England]]. The Arnolds gathered their baggage and supplies in the spring of 1635 and made the trip from [[Ilchester]] to [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] on the coast of [[Devon]].{{sfn |Arnold|1921|p=38}}  He wrote in a family record begun by his father, "Memorandom my father and his family Sett Sayle from [[Dartmouth, England|Dartmouth]] in Old England, the first of May, friday &c. Arrived in New England June 24o Ano 1635."{{sfn|Hubbard|1879|p=428}}  The name of the ship on which he sailed was not recorded, nor has it been identified since.{{sfn|Arnold|1921|p=9}}  It is possible that [[Stukeley Westcott]] of [[Yeovil]]<ref>Which is five miles south of Ilchester</ref> was also on the same ship with his family, including his daughter Damaris, aged 15, the future wife of Arnold.{{sfn|Whitman|1932|p=13}}

Upon their arrival in New England, the Arnolds joined a group of settlers from [[Hingham, Norfolk|Hingham]], [[Norfolk]], England, where they established the new town of [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]] in the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]].{{sfn|Anderson|Sanborn|Sanborn|1999|p=84}}  William Arnold received title to a house lot here in September 1635, but the following spring he and several other settlers were persuaded by [[Roger Williams (theologian)|Roger Williams]] to join him in establishing a new settlement on the [[Narragansett Bay]] named Providence Plantation.{{sfn|Anderson |Sanborn|Sanborn|1999|p=84}}  The younger Arnold wrote in the family record, "Memm. We came to Providence to Dwell the 20th of April, 1636. per me Bennedict Arnold."{{Sfn|Hubbard|1879|p=428}}  Arnold received a house lot on what is now North Main Street in Providence, and his father was granted the second lot south of his.{{sfn|Arnold|1921|p=21}}

==Providence and Pawtuxet==

In 1637, Arnold was [[List of early settlers of Rhode Island#Providence civil compact, 1637|one of 13 settlers]] who signed a compact agreeing to subject themselves to any agreements made by a majority of the masters of families.{{sfn|Appletons|1891}}{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=1}}  About 1638, he accompanied his father, his brother-in-law [[William Carpenter (Rhode Island)|William Carpenter]], and [[Robert Coles (settler)|Robert Coles]] in a move about five miles south to the [[Pawtuxet River]].  The settlement was called Pawtuxet and was still within the jurisdiction of Providence Plantation; it later became a part of [[Cranston, Rhode Island]].  On 17 July 1640, Arnold signed an agreement [[List of early settlers of Rhode Island#Signers of Providence agreement for a government, 1640|with 38 other Providence residents]] to form a more compact government "to preserve the peace and insure the prosperity of a growing community."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}  It did neither, especially after the arrival of [[Samuel Gorton]], who [[Roger Williams (theologian)|Roger Williams]] wrote was "bewitching and bemadding poor Providence."{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=302}}  In one incident, "Upon the attempt to enforce the execution of an award against Francis Weston made by eight men orderly chosen, Gorton, with many of his followers, assailed the representatives of law and order making a tumultuous hubbub."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}  Arnold wrote a petition with 12 others dated 17 November 1641 in which they formally applied to Massachusetts for help, asking the government there to "lend us a neighborlike helping hand."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}  Massachusetts replied that they could not help unless the complainants fell under their jurisdiction.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}

The Arnolds, Coles, and Carpenter were highly offended by Gorton, who had moved with some of his adherents to Pawtuxet. They went to Boston and submitted themselves to the government and jurisdiction of Massachusetts on 2 September 1642.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}  They were received by the General Court there and appointed justices of the peace.  In doing this, these settlers allowed a foreign jurisdiction into the midst of the Providence government, a condition that lasted for 16 years.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=3}}  Gorton was unhappy about being under the jurisdiction of Massachusetts and moved with his followers another 12 miles farther south, settling beyond the limits of Massachusetts' jurisdiction at a place called Shawomet.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=4}}

[[File:Original Providence Rhode Island town layout of homesteads.jpg|thumb|left|Original town layout of Providence showing Arnold's lot, sixth from the top]]

Arnold and his father had already become proficient in the [[Narragansett people|Narragansett]] and [[Wampanoag]] languages, and both harbored an intense dislike of Gorton. They devised a scheme to undermine their adversary and to simultaneously obtain extensive lands from the local Indians.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|pp=4,6}}  Gorton had purchased Shawomet from [[Miantonomi]], the chief [[sachem]] of the Narragansett people.  Minor sachems Ponham and Sacononoco had some control of the lands at Pawtuxet and Shawomet, and Arnold, acting as interpreter, took these chieftains to [[John Winthrop|Governor Winthrop]] in Boston and had them submit themselves and their lands to Massachusetts, claiming that the sale of Shawomet to Gorton was done "under duress."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=4}}  Now with a claim to Shawomet, Massachusetts directed Gorton and his followers to appear in Boston to answer "complaints" made by the two minor sachems.  When Gorton refused, Massachusetts sent a party to Shawomet to arrest him and his neighbors.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=4}}  The ensuing trial had nothing to do with the land claims, but instead focused on the writings and beliefs of Gorton, for which he and others in his group were imprisoned.  Ultimately, Gorton was released and went to England where he was given legal title to his lands from the Earl of Warwick and, in his honor, the settlement of Shawomet was renamed [[Warwick, Rhode Island|Warwick]].{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=4}}

Arnold was the only member of the colony besides Roger Williams who was highly proficient in the Narragansett and Wampanoag tongues, and he was often called upon to interpret during negotiations.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=6}}  In June 1645, he was sent by the General Court of Massachusetts to the [[Narragansett people]] to urge them to desist from engaging in a war with the [[Mohegans]].  On 28 July, Arnold and two others were sent to get the hostile tribes to send deputies to Boston to talk and make peace.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=6}}  This attempt failed and, a month later, Arnold would not go back again, as he had been charged with misrepresenting the reply of the tribes, and Roger Williams went as interpreter in his place.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=6}}{{sfn|Appletons|1891}}

The issue of the Pawtuxet settlers remaining under the jurisdiction of Massachusetts was a constant irritant to Roger Williams, Gorton, and the other Providence and Warwick settlers.  The General Court of Rhode Island met at Warwick on 22 May 1649 and ordered that letters be sent to Arnold and the other Pawtuxet settlers in reference to their subjecting themselves to the Rhode Island colony.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=6}}  This did not happen, and the Pawtuxet settlers continued under Massachusetts for another nine years.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}}  Arnold and his father did not specifically lay claim to the Shawomet lands; nevertheless, they had extensive land holdings, and Arnold paid a tax of five pounds in 1650, the highest in the colony, and his father paid three and a half pounds, the second highest amount.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=6}}{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}}

In June 1650, Roger Williams wrote to [[John Winthrop|Governor Winthrop]] in Massachusetts saying that Arnold had bought a house and land at [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] with the intention to move there.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=7}}  His reasons for moving were not revealed in his own writings, but some historians have suggested that mercantile interests compelled the move,{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=7}} while others have suggested political interests or a desire to get away from the hostile atmosphere of Providence and Pawtuxet.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1025}}

==Newport and politics==

In 1651, Arnold left Providence and Pawtuxet for Aquidneck Island (which was officially called Rhode Island at the time), settling in Newport.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1016}}  He recorded in the family record, "Memorandum. We came from Providence with our family to Dwell at Newport in Rhode Island the 19th of November, Thursday in afternoon, & arrived ye same night  Ano. Domina 1651".{{sfn|Hubbard|1879|p=428}}  With only a few exceptions, men from Newport held the reins of power for the first century of Rhode Island history.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1019}}  When the first English settlers came to [[Aquidneck Island]] in 1638, they organized a quarterly court and English-style jury trial.  In 1640, Newport established monthly courts, rights of appeal, and trial by jury, whereas in Providence there was no court, no judge, and no jury.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1018}}  

Significant political events were taking place upon Arnold's arrival in Newport.  [[William Coddington]] had been successful in separating the island towns of Newport and Portsmouth from the two mainland towns of Providence and Warwick (called Shawhomett at the time), under a commission which he obtained earlier in England; he was appointed as governor for life of the two island towns in 1651.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=7}}  Providence sent [[Roger Williams (theologian)|Roger Williams]] to England, feeling that the Patent of 1643 had been abandoned, and those on the island opposed to Coddington sent [[Dr. John Clarke]] and [[Mary Dyer|William Dyer]] to have Coddington's charter annulled.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=7}}  Williams and Dyer returned to New England after finding success, while Clarke remained in England for the next decade, acting as a diplomat to protect the colony's interests.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1019}}  In February 1653, Dyer brought letters revoking Coddington's commission, with the authority of the government to proceed under the Patent of 1643 and the status quo of 1647.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=7}}  [[John Sanford (governor)|John Sanford]] succeeded Coddington in 1653, and with the change of administration came the work leading to the reunification of the four towns under one government.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1009}}  

In 1653, Arnold became a [[freeman (colonial)|freeman]] of Newport and, from that point forward, served in some public capacity every year until his death in 1678.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1016}}  In 1654, he was selected as one of the commissioners from Newport (each of the four towns had six), and he was an Assistant from 1655 to 1656.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}}  He was very active as a member of the Court of Commissioners and a member of the most important committees.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=8}}  In 1655, Arnold, Roger Williams, Samuel Gorton, and [[William Baulston]] were appointed by the court to frame a letter of thanksgiving to the English Lord President of the Council on colonial affairs, and to present humble acknowledgments and submission of the colony to His Highness, the Lord Protector, [[Oliver Cromwell]]. The letter of reply from Cromwell was placed in the custody of Arnold.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=8}}  

Arnold was elected as the President of the colony in 1657, at the age of 41, succeeding Roger Williams in this capacity.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1017}}

===Terms as president===

[[File:Roger Williams statue by Franklin Simmons.jpg|thumb|right| Roger Williams was succeeded by Arnold as President of the colony in 1657]]

Arnold became President at a crucial time in Rhode Island's history.  Tremendous political change was occurring in England, and this resulted in significant changes and opportunities for the little [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]], which was constantly being harassed by its larger neighbors Massachusetts and Connecticut.  Oliver Cromwell had been ruling in England since the overthrow and execution of King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] in 1649, but his death in 1658 marked the [[Restoration (1660)|restoration]] of the monarchy, and [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] ascended to the throne.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1019}}  The Colony of Rhode Island was quick to adjust to the new political reality, and the General Court of Commissioners met at Warwick on 18 October 1660 where two letters were read, one from Dr. Clarke telling of the Restoration, and one from His Majesty, containing the royal declaration and proclamation.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1019}}  Leaders in the colony set aside a special day of proclamation so that the colonists could recognize the new king.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1019}}

Arnold was succeeded as President in 1660 by [[William Brenton]], but continued for many years as a Commissioner, as well as an Assistant from 1660 to 1661.{{sfn|Austin|1887|pp=242-7}}  In these roles, he headed a committee to draft and send a new commission to Dr. Clarke, giving due credit to the King's father Charles I for the Patent of 1643 which gave the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations its official existence.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1020}}  Reference was made to "sundry obstructions" stemming from "claims of neighbors about us," referring to interests that both the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]] and [[Connecticut Colony]] had on the greater Narragansett Bay area.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1020}}  The document went on to include Dr. Clarke as the agent and attorney for the colony, and used deferential language toward "his most gracious and regall Majesty, Charles the Second, by the Grace of God, the most mighty and potent King of England."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1020}}  

In this commission, the four towns of the Rhode Island colony declared their "unfayned affection" for the new king.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1020}}  The commission also armed Dr. Clarke, the able diplomat, with what he needed to fulfill his mission.  He wrote a well-crafted letter on behalf of the colony asking for an experiment in liberty where the colony would become "a Republic of Liberty under Law, in which every man is king and no man subject."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1021}}

===Dealings with the Quakers===

A 1658 letter from the [[New England Confederation|United Colonies]] (Massachusetts, Plymouth, New Haven, and Connecticut) announced the arrival of the [[Quakers]], calling them notorious heretics and calling for their speedy removal from the colonies.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  The United Colonies wanted the Quakers removed from Newport, and used the threat of withholding trade as leverage for their position.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  Arnold was no friend of the Quakers, but his reply demonstrated a firm adherence to the Rhode Island doctrine of religious tolerance and was endorsed by the four Assistants (one from each town).{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  He wrote, "Concerning these Quakers (so-called), which are now among us, we have no law among us, whereby to punish any for only declaring by words, &c., theire mindes and understandings concerning the things and days of God, as to salvation and an eternal condition."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  He went on to say that the Quakers find a "delight to be persecuted by civill powers," thus gaining more adherents to their cause.  He felt that their doctrines tended to be very absolute, "cutting down and overturning relations and civil government among men."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}

President Arnold promised Massachusetts Governor [[Simon Bradstreet]] that the Quakers' "extravagent outgoinges" would be considered at the next session of the General Assembly, and he hoped that some action would be taken to prevent the "bad effects of their doctrines and endeavors."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  At the March 1658 session of the Assembly, the Rhode Island doctrine of "freedom of different consciences" was reaffirmed, and a letter was sent to the Commissioners stating that the matter would be presented to the supreme authority of England if troubles arose from harboring Quakers.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1024}}  Following this, no further complaints came from the other colonies.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1025}}

===Terms as governor===

[[File:Rhode Island State Charter 1663.jpg|thumb|right| The [[Royal Charter of 1663]] named Arnold as the first governor of the colony.]]

In 1662, Arnold was once again elected president of the colony, and Clarke's earlier diplomacy came to fruition in the second year of this term with the [[Royal Charter of 1663]], which historian [[Thomas Bicknell]] described as "the grandest instrument of human liberty ever constructed."{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1022}}  Under this instrument, Arnold became the first governor of the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, with [[William Brenton]] as his Deputy.{{sfn|Laws of Nature}}{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1022}}  The earlier governing body, the Court of Commissioners, was replaced with a legislature of ten Assistants and a House of Deputies, with six from Newport and four each from Providence, Portsmouth, and Warwick.{{sfn|Arnold |1859|p=295}}  One of the first acts performed by Arnold as governor was to address a letter to [[John Winthrop, Jr.|Governor Winthrop]] of Connecticut about running a line between the two colonies as provided by the Charter.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=10}}  

In 1664, the King's Commissioners came to Rhode Island to settle claims of jurisdiction over the Narragansett country, specifically addressing rival claims between the Rhode Island and Connecticut colonies over land at [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] and the settlement at [[Wickford, Rhode Island|Wickford]].{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}{{sfn|Arnold| 1859|pp=304-5}}  The commissioners were able to forestall a major confrontation, but no substantial changes were made, and the disputes between the two colonies continued for the next 50 years.{{sfn|Arnold|1859|p=305}}  The King's Commissioners also appointed Arnold as a justice of the peace and a magistrate of the "King's Province" (later [[Washington County, Rhode Island]]).{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}

In the election of 1666, Arnold retired from office and was succeeded once again by [[William Brenton]].{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  Nevertheless, he and others were compelled to sit in the Assembly as deputies "as the Court due desire their assistance."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  In 1669, Arnold was again chosen as governor, and he was re-elected in 1670 when the controversy became acute with Connecticut over disputed lands in King's Province and [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]].{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  On 11 July 1670, Arnold sent a strong letter to Connecticut's Governor Winthrop informing him of Rhode Island's determination to appeal to King Charles concerning "invasions and intrusions upon the lands and government of this Colony."{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  There is no record, however, of this threat being carried through.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}

During this administration, the [[Quakers]] were finding the religious tolerance of Rhode Island to be a fertile ground for their missionaries, and they also found a safe haven from other colonies here.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  They found success in the spread of their religion and became a strong political force, as well.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=11}}  Arnold was once again elected governor in 1671 but, in 1672, the governorship went to Quaker [[Nicholas Easton]], and the Quakers held the reins of power for three of the next five years.  Arnold, however, had left a positive mark on the colony and, after more than ten years of his leadership, the disorganized and fragmentary governments of the four towns were united and put in order, with courts established and an organized society put into motion.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1022}}

===Business and land interests===

[[File:somerset levels from glastonbury tor arp.jpg|thumb|left|Arnold's New England property called "Lemmington Farm" was named after [[Limington]] in Somerset.]]

Arnold's usefulness had been in great demand for the welfare of the colony, and his successful political career was mirrored by equally successful agricultural and mercantile pursuits.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=12}}  While living at Pawtuxet, he became an agent for arms, ammunition, and liquors, and he had an establishment on the Warwick side of the river offering Boston goods and provisions in demand at the time.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=12}}  In his book ''Simplicities Defense'', [[Samuel Gorton]] complained that Arnold constantly traded with the Indians on the Sabbath day and was too liberal in providing them with powder.  He further complained that Arnold would not sell items to the Warwick settlers unless they submitted themselves to the jurisdiction of Massachusetts.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=12}}  The Warwick settlers also complained that he furnished the Indians with strong drink and wine, which was forbidden by the Warwick town council.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=12}}

After leaving the governorship in 1672, Arnold likely attended to his commercial interests, and he was said to be the wealthiest person in the colony.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=12}}  He had a wharf and warehouse mentioned in his will, and he had commercial interests in the [[West Indies]], evident from a 1674 letter that he wrote to his son-in-law Roger Goulding, urging him to complete his (Arnold's) business in the [[Barbados]].{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=13}}

Arnold held several parcels of land in and around Newport, one of which he called his "Lemmington Farm," which was named after the village of Limington in his native [[Somerset]], England.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}}   In 1657, he was one of about a hundred individuals who purchased [[Conanicut Island]], the second largest island in the Narragansett Bay where the town of [[Jamestown, Rhode Island|Jamestown]] is now located.{{sfn|Appletons|1891}}  He and [[John Greene, Jr.|John Greene]] also acquired Goat Island and Coaster's Harbor Island, which later became the property of the town of Newport.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919| p=16}}

Sometime after January 1658, he [[List of early settlers of Rhode Island#Pettaquamscutt purchasers|and six others]] held equal shares of interest in a company that bought a large tract of land in the Narragansett country known as the Pettaquamscutt Purchase, a tract that became [[South Kingstown]], Rhode Island.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=17}}  He held this until his death, when the property was bequeathed to his three sons Benedict, Josiah, and Oliver.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=17}}  He also owned two parcels of land in Newport, one where his wharf and warehouse were located, and the other the site of his mansion house.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=17}}

===King Philip's War===

[[King Philip's War]] (1675–76) left the mainland towns of Rhode Island in ruins, "the most disastrous conflict to ever devastate New England."{{sfn|Arnold|1859|p=387}}  This confrontation between several tribes and the Colonists was named for [[Metacomet]], sachem of the [[Wampanoag]]s, who was also called King Philip. The Rhode Island colony was much more at peace with the Indians than the other colonies, yet it bore the brunt of damage because of its location at the geographical center of conflict; the settlements of Warwick and Pawtuxet were totally destroyed, with much of Providence destroyed, as well.{{sfn|Gorton|1907|p=136}}  Several of Arnold's relatives lived in these areas and fled to [[Long Island]], and his aged father had been moved from Pawtuxet to his brother's garrison house but did not survive the conflict.{{sfn|Arnold|1935|p=48}}  

In April 1676, it was voted by the Assembly "that in these troublesome times and straits in this Colony, this Assembly desiring to have the advice and concurrence of the most judicious inhabitants, if it may be had for the good of the whole, do desire at their next sitting the company and counsel of Mr. Benedict Arnold" [[List of early settlers of Rhode Island#Colonial leaders during King Phillips War|and 15 others]].{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1022}}  Quakers were noted for their pacifism, and Quaker Governor [[Walter Clarke (governor)|Walter Clarke]] was in office during the conflict.  Even though the war had ended, the so-called "war party" was successful in the election of 1677, and Arnold was voted back into office as governor.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=13}}

During this term, Arnold's health began to fail, but he was still re-elected in May 1678.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=15}}  He was too ill to leave his house, and his deputy governor [[John Cranston (politician)|John Cranston]] transacted the colony's business, along with two assistants and a recorder, by visiting him at home.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=15}}  His health did not improve, and he died within a month of his last election to governor.{{sfn|Tompkins|1919|p=15}}

==Death and legacy==

[[File:DSCN3887 newporttower e.jpg|thumb|right| The [[Newport Tower (Rhode Island)|Newport Tower]] which Arnold called his "stone built wind mill"]]

Arnold wrote his will on 24 December 1677, during his last full term as governor.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}} A codicil to the will was written the following February, and the governor died in June while still in office.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=242}}  On 29 June, Samuel Hubbard of Newport wrote to Dr. Edward Stennett of London, "Our Governor died the 19th day of June, 1678, buried 20th day, all this island was invited, many others was there, judged near a thousand people, brother Hiscox spoke there excellently led forth, I praise God."{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=244}} In his will, Governor Arnold gave land to his wife with mansion house and "''stone built wind mill''."{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=244}}  There are romantic legends of early norsemen coming to Newport and building the stone structure that continues to stand in the city, but the strongest evidence suggests that the structure was the base of Arnold's windmill mentioned in his will.{{sfn|Godfrey|1951|p=129}}

Benedict Arnold, his wife, and many of his family are buried in the [[Arnold Burying Ground]] located on Pelham Street in Newport.  For many years, the cemetery was buried under a garden in the back yard of a residence, but a major renovation began in 1949 whereby all the stones were unearthed, cleaned, and returned to their original positions.{{sfn|Brayton|1960|p=77}}  There is no inscription on the slabs covering the graves of the governor and his wife, but his grave is marked with a governor's medallion.{{sfn|Find-a-grave|2005}}

Lieutenant Governor and Rhode Island historian [[Samuel G. Arnold]] wrote of him:
<blockquote>That he was no friend of the doctrines, or advocate of the conduct of the followers of [[George Fox|Fox]] [Quakers] is evident from his writings; but that like [[Roger Williams (theologian)|Williams]], he recognized the distinction between persecution and opposition, between legal force and moral suasion as applied to matters of opinion, is equally apparent.  In politics and in theology he was alike the opponent of [[William Coddington|Coddington]] and the friend of [[Dr. John Clarke|John Clarke]] and throughout his long and useful life he displayed talents of a brilliant order which were ever employed for the welfare of his fellow men.{{sfn|Bicknell|1920|p=1023}}</blockquote>

==Family and descendants==

Arnold was married on 17 December 1640 to Damaris, the daughter of [[Stukeley Westcott]] and Julianna Marchante.{{sfn|Cutter|1915|p=45}}  They had nine children:  Benedict, Caleb, Josiah, Damaris, William, Penelope, Oliver, Godsgift, and Freelove.{{sfn|Austin|1887|p=243}}  All but William grew to adulthood, married, and had children.{{sfn|Austin|1887
|pp=243,245}}  His son Caleb, a physician, married Abigail Wilbur, who was the daughter of [[Samuel Wilbur, Jr.]] and the granddaughter of both [[Samuel Wilbore]] [Sr.] and [[John Porter (settler)|John Porter]], two signers of the [[Portsmouth Compact|compact]] establishing the town of Portsmouth with [[Anne Hutchinson]].

Notable descendants of Benedict Arnold through his son Benedict include his great-grandson, also named [[Benedict Arnold]],{{sfn|Arnold|1935|p=132}} the general of the [[American Revolutionary War]] who is remembered primarily for his treason to America when he switched sides to fight with the British.  Descendants through his son Caleb Arnold include Commodore [[Oliver Hazard Perry]],{{sfn|Arnold|1935|p=90}} American hero of the [[Great Lakes]] during the [[War of 1812]], and his younger brother Commodore [[Matthew C. Perry]],{{sfn|Arnold|1935|p=90}} who compelled the [[opening of Japan]] to the West with the [[Convention of Kanagawa]] in 1854. Senator [[Stephen Arnold Douglas]]{{sfn|Arnold|1935|p=274}} is also descended through this line, who debated [[Abraham Lincoln]] in 1858 before a senate race and later lost to him in the [[1860 presidential election]].  Rhode Island colonial Deputy Governor [[George Hazard]] is another descendant.{{sfn|Austin|1887|pp=244,320-1}}

