[[File:Heaving the lead.jpg|thumb|Heaving the lead. A man standing in the chains.]]
{{About|part of a ship|defensive chains to control access to harbours and rivers|boom (navigational barrier)}}
The '''chains''' were small platforms, built on either side of the [[hull (watercraft)|hull]] of a ship, used to provide a wide purchase for the shrouds, and to assist in the practice of [[depth sounding]]. 

The chains provided a platform for a 'leadsman', the sailor assigned to swing the sounding line, or 'lead' into the water.<ref name="Kemp">{{cite book |editor=Kemp|title=The Oxford Companion to Ships and the Sea|page=150}}</ref> The term originated from the practice of the sailor standing between the [[Shroud (sailing)|shrouds]] when casting the line, which were attached to the hull by [[chainplate]]s, or, in earlier sailing ships, to lengths of chain along the ship's side. A length of chain was usually fixed at waist height to the [[stanchion]]s above the chains, as an added safety measure.<ref name="Kemp"/> The chains were common on large sailing vessels, but the role of leadsman and swinging the lead to obtain depth soundings declined with developments in [[echo sounding]], and ships are rarely now equipped with chains.<ref name="Kemp"/>

