{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2016}} '''John Atirau Asher''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|OBE|size=85%}} (8 August 1892 &ndash; 14 December 1966) was a New Zealand tribal leader, hotelier, interpreter and racehorse owner. Of [[Māori people|Māori]] descent, he identified with the [[Ngati Pikiao]], [[Ngati Pukenga]] and [[Te Arawa]] [[iwi]]. He was born in [[Tauranga]], New Zealand, on 8 August 1892.<ref name="DNZB Asher">{{DNZB|title=John Atirau Asher|first= Ringakapo Tirangaro|last= Asher-Payne|id=4a21|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>
Asher was the second-youngest of 11 children—his brothers included [[Ernie Asher|Ernie]] and [[Albert Asher]].
In the [[1965 Birthday Honours|1965 Queen's Birthday Honours]], Asher was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] for services to the Māori people.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=43669 |date=12 June 1965 |page=5514 |supp=y }}</ref>
