'''Lutfullah Halimi''' ({{lang-ota|لطف الله حليمى|translit=Lutfullâh Halîmî}}, {{lang-fa|لطف الله حلیمی|translit=Loṭf-Allāh Ḥalimi}}; died 1516) was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] poet and lexicographer of [[Persian people|Persian]] origin.

==Biography==
Halimi was born to a certain Abi Yusof.{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}} Information about his place of birth and education remains unclear.{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}} According to [[Aşık Çelebi]], Halimi had migrated from Iran and climbed up the ladder through the support of [[Mahmud Pasha Angelović|Mahmud Pasha]], the grand vizier at the time.{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}} Sources of a later time state that Halimi hailed from [[Amasya]] near the [[Black Sea]].{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}} According to his own works, Halimi had moved from Iran whereafter he was made tutor to Prince Mehmed (later known as Sultan [[Mehmed the Conqueror]], i.e. Mehmed II).{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}}

It is likely that Halimi became the judge of [[Sivas]] during the 2nd reign of Mehmed the Conqueror.{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}}

According to [[Kâtip Çelebi]], Halimi's death was the result of murder.{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}}

==Works==
Halimi's known works are:{{sfn|Yazici|2003|pages=588-589}}{{sfn|Storey|1984|pages=63-64}}

* ''Bahr al-gharaeb / Loghat-e Halimi'' (a Persian-Turkish dictionary, found in numerous libraries under various names, such as "Qasemiya", "Qaema", or "Nethar al-malek")
* ''Mosharrahat al-asma'' (an Arabic-Persian dictionary)
* ''Tebb-e manzum'' (a Persian work on medicine, dedicated to Mehmed the Conqueror. In the preface, Halimi states that he is in "great debt in learning medicine to Greek physicians", and elaborates that "he preferred to use Persian instead of Arabic in a versified work, because he believed that there was no language as refined and graceful as Persian". Lastly, he "acknowledges his debt to [[Avicenna]]'s ''Qanun and Shefa''".)
* ''Sharh moktasar al-ashkal'' (a short treatise on Islamic law, in Arabic)
* ''Qasida-ye ta'iya'' (an Arabic poem. It was presented to Sultan Mehmed the Conqueror. In the poem, Halimi praises the sultan and mentions the "misfortunes" that he himself had endured during his life. "Ḥalimi describes the ideal relationship between rulers and religious leaders, and recounts the attitudes of previous rulers on this issue while chastising fraudulent scholars". In between the sentences, Persian couplets and stories are inserted.)

