{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}
'''Shirish Pai''' ([[Devanagari]]: शिरीष पै) (15 November 1929<ref name="birth">[http://www.loksatta.com/mumbai-news/marathi-poet-playwriter-journalist-ms-shirish-pai-passes-away-in-mumbai-1543605/ लेखिका आणि सामाजिक कार्यकर्त्या शिरीष पै यांचे निधन] {{mr icon}}</ref> – 2 September 2017<ref name="death">[http://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/marathi-poet-activist-shirish-pai-passes-away/article19609880.ece Marathi poet, activist Shirish Pai passes away]</ref>) was  a social worker and a writer from [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. She had written in [[Marathi language|Marathi]] and [[English language|English]], primarily the former.

== Early life ==
Shirish is the elder daughter of [[Prahlad Keshav Atre|Acharya Atre]]. She has a college degree in Law from Government College of Law, Mumbai.{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}}

== Career ==
She joined her father's newspaper, ''Maratha'', as a journalist.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=Articles&ArticleID=13198|title = Shirish Pai – An Introduction|date = |accessdate = 9 August 2015|website = Boloji|publisher = |last = Thiagarajan|first = A.}}</ref> She was deeply influenced by the Soviet thinking and way of life, and toured the [[Soviet Union]] and other Eastern Block countries.{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}} Alongside her father, Shirish played a role in the [[Samyukta Maharashtra]] movement.{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}}

== Writing ==
She has written several books; they include collections of her poems. She introduced the [[haiku]] form of poetry to [[Marathi literature]] in 1975.<ref name=":0" /> She has also translated Japanese haiku into Maranthi and English.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thehaikufoundation.org/omeka/files/original/338c0717357ce525a55926efc61d35d0.pdf|title = A History of Indian Haiku|date = |accessdate = 9 August 2015|website = The Haiku Foundation|publisher = |last = Ramesh|first = Kala}}</ref> Her literary work has received several national and state awards.

In a newspaper interview in June 2011 she revealed that she had started writing and composing poems from the time she was in secondary school and received great encouragement from her father in this regard.{{Citation needed|date = August 2015}}

== Family ==
Shirish was married to lawyer and journalist Vyankatesh Pai. They have two sons, Rajendra Pai and Vikramaditya Pai who are both lawyers. She resided, and died, in Mumbai.<ref name="death" />

